.chap(Useful Built-In Functions,builtin)

Now that we have gained some proficiency in composing
PPL statements and writing programs, there are a
number of important operations we need to be able to
perform in order to solve more complex problems using PPL.
These include saving programs for later use, accessing
programs previously stored away, printing formatted
numbers, converting data from one type to another,
computing mathematical functions, and many others.

PPL contains a number of built-in functions for performing
such operations.  We shall take up some of them here and
defer the remainder until Sections {section! builtinuser} and {chapter! advanced}.  A complete summary
of built-in functions, including the ones associated with
unary and binary operators, is given in {"Appendix!" appbuiltin}.

.sec(Saving and Restoring Programs,saving)

PPL contains several mechanisms for %<saving/program>s
.x restoring program
.x program,restoring
and data on !<files> for use in a subsequent
.x file
session.  Two of these are described here and the remainder
in {"Section!" fileio}.  The system functions involved are ~<<SAVE>~,
~<<RESTORE>~, ~<<READ>~, and ~<<WRITE>~.
Each of these functions takes a single argument which
is a ~&/<STRING/description of/file>~ describing the file
to be read or written.

Since different operating systems use different conventions
for naming files, the most complete possible form of this file
specification string varies depending on the operating system
under which PPL is running.  Under the @/<DECsystem-10,filename format/in> (PDP-10)
operating system, the form is:
.see name,file,filename format
.see device,filename format
.see directory,filename format
.see extension,file,filename format
.see version,file,filename format
.see subdirectory,filename format

.begin nofill tabs 9

\"!<dev>:!<name>.!<ext>[!<proj>,!<prog>]"
.end

where !<dev>: is the device name, !<name> is the filename (up to
6 characters), .!<ext> is the extension (up to 3 characters),
and [!<proj>,!<prog>] is the user project-programmer (account) number.

Under the @/<Tenex,filename format/in> (PDP-10) operating system, the filename syntax
is as follows:

.begin nofill tabs 9

\"!<dev>:<!<directory>>!<name>.!<extension>;!<version>"
.end

where !<dev>: is the device name, <!<directory>> is the name of the
owner of the file, !<name> and .!<extension> are the arbitrary
user-chosen filename and extension (up to 39 characters each),
and ;!<version> is a version number of up to 6 digits.

Finally, under the @/<Unix,filename format/in> (PDP-11) operating system,
files are named as follows:

.begin nofill tabs 9

\"/!<directory>/!<subdirectory>/ ... /!<name>.!<extension><!<protection>>"

.end

where !<directory> and !<subdirectory> conform to Unix
conventions for device and directory specification
and !<name> and .!<extension> are as explained above.
If the last character of a filename is a period, it
is removed, allowing the user to specify files with no
extensions.
The <!<protection>> field is a three-digit octal number
representing standard Unix precedence.

In all cases, however, portions of the file specification not
supplied by the user are defaulted to standard values.
In particular, the default device is the disk, the default
directory is your own (or your current connected or attached directory), and the default extension is ~.PPL~
(for ~READ~ and ~WRITE~) or ~.ENV~ (for ~SAVE~ and ~RESTORE~).
Hence, in most situations, users need supply only the !<name>
portion of the specification. (If this is restricted to
six or fewer letters and digits, then specifications
of the form "!<name>" will be compatible across all operating
systems under which PPL presently runs).

{fn(SAVE,s)} and {fn(RESTORE,s)} are built-in functions for
saving and restoring entire working environments.
.x environment,saving and restoring
.see saving environment,SAVE
.see restoring environment,RESTORE
The ~SAVE~ function writes out (onto the file described
by the ~STRING~ !<s>) all functions, definitions,
data, and control status in binary format (machine-readable
only).  At some later time, the ~RESTORE~ function
may be used to restore the same working environment.
Indeed, if ~SAVE~ was given during the execution of
some function, that function will resume automatically
upon restoration of the environment.
~RESTORE~ !<replaces> the current environment
by the one read from the file;  that is, it is not
possible to !<merge> environments by this means.

The ~<<READ>~ and ~<<WRITE>~ system functions deal
with 7<<ASCII>* (character) rather than binary
information.  {fn(WRITE,s)} causes all currently-defined
@@<function,writing onto file>s, @@<data definition,writing onto file>s, and @@<operator definition,writing onto file>s
to be written out onto the file described by
the ~STRING~ !<s>.
(Data and operator definitions will be introduced in
{"Chapter!" extension}).
If !<s> is omitted, the output will be printed on
the terminal.  Since the file is in character format,
it may be read by systems other than PPL
(e.g. Teco) or be listed by the monitor Type command.
{fn(READ,s)} causes the data in the named file
to be treated exactly as if it were teletype input.*<Due to
an implementation deficiency, READ(s) should be given only as
a direct command in PPL-10.>
It is the user's responsibility to ensure that definitions
in the current environment do not conflict with those
in the file being read.  Usually, one wants to
issue an ~@@<ERASE,issued before READ>()~ command
(see {"Section!" erasing}) to clear the current environment
before ~READ~ing a new program (though this is not
always the case).
If an error occurs during a ~READ~, the
operation is terminated.  As usual, the statement
that caused the error may be displayed by pressing
the <<Escape> key.

The ~WRITE~ and ~READ~ functions are to be
preferred for long-term storage of programs, even though
they save less information (i.e. they do not save
the values of global or local variables, nor do they
remember any control information).  This is for several
reasons:

(1) ~SAVE~d environments result in much larger files
than those created by ~WRITE~.
User file storage may be limited
on some computer systems.

(2) It is not possible to access the information in
a ~SAVE~d file outside of PPL.

(3) Whenever a new version of PPL is loaded onto the
system, old environments are no longer restorable.
.x environment file,invalidation of
This is because a ~SAVE~d environment reflects
much of the internal structure of PPL, which is likely
to change from version to version.

Thus, ~SAVE~ is really designed only
for short-term storage, such as
during debugging or when a long computation must be interrupted.
~WRITE~ should be used for permanent or long-term storage.

Functions for reading and writing files of data under program
control are described in {"Section!" fileio}.

.sec(Recording a Terminal Session,protocol)
.x PROTOCOL
.x UNPROTOCOL

In many cases, such as when using a display terminal which
does not produce hard-copy output, it is useful to be able to
record a session with PPL that may later be printed out.
In order to allow this operation, PPL includes a pair of
functions ~PROTOCOL~ and ~UNPROTOCOL~ which causes a record
of the entire terminal session to be written to the
file ~PPL.PROTOCOL~.*<Currently, the ~PROTOCOL~ and ~UNPROTOCOL~
funtions are defined in PPL-11 only.
When these functions are implemented for the PDP-10, the filename
will be changed to ~PROTO.PPL~ to conform to PDP-10 filename conventions.>
The recording begins just after the ~PROTOCOL~ command is executed
and consists of all user input and PPL responses until just after
the execution of an ~UNPROTOCOL~ or ~SYS~ command.

Following the conclusion of a particular PPL session, the protocol
file may then be printed by commands to the operating system.
In order to record more than one PPL session, it is necessary
to rename the ~PPL.PROTOCOL~ file before beginning the second
session to avoid overwriting the original protocol.

.sec(Erasing Identifiers,erasing)
.see identifier,erasing,ERASE
.see function,erasing,ERASE
.x ERASE

Occasionally it is necessary to erase the values of
variables or the definitions of functions.
For example, we might want to erase the definition of
~FACT~ so that we could define a new one.  To prevent
unintentional user errors, PPL does not allow
a function to be redefined until its old definition
is explicitly deleted by the user.

To erase a user-defined function, a call should be made
to the built-in function ~ERASE~, giving as its argument
the name of the function to be deleted !<preceded by
a dollar sign>.  The reason for this latter requirement
.x dollar sign,preceding argument to ERASE
will be explained in {"Section!" moreerase}; failure to observe
this precaution may lead to very unexpected results.
For example, the ~FACT~ function is deleted
by the command

.examp
\ERASE($FACT)
.end


~ERASE~ is an example of a !<variadic function>, i.e.
.x variadic function
.x function,variadic
a function that may take a varying number of arguments.
Thus, if ~ERASE~ is called with two or more arguments
(separated by commas), the value or definition of each
such identifier will be ~ERASE~d.  ~ERASE~ has
a special operation if it is called with !<no> arguments;
namely, the entire @@<environment,erasing> is cleared (just as if PPL
had been started over, which is in fact what happens).
To call ~ERASE~ with no arguments requires an empty
set of @@<parentheses,required in variadic function call>.  This is the case for calling
any variadic function with zero arguments.
In this respect, variadic functions should be distinguished from
functions that !<never> take arguments, such as
~RESET~; in the latter case, the empty parentheses
are not necessary.

In the rare case in which it is necessary, it is also
.see built-in function,erasing,ERASE
legal to ~ERASE~ a built-in function.  For example,
if a file created by ~WRITE~ contained a user-defined
function whose name was later used as the name of a built-in
function in a new version of PPL, it would no longer
be possible to ~READ~ the old file because of the name
conflict.  In this case, the user could first ~ERASE~
the built-in function before attempting to ~READ~ the old file.

.sec(More on Numbers,morenumbers)

A more formal presentation of the text representation
of @@<number,representation of>s will now be presented. In particular,
it is necessary to become familiar with the
lexical contexts within which numeric constants
are recognized.

In scanning from left to right in a statement,
PPL will recognize a number (~@@<INT,numeric representation>~, ~@@<REAL,numeric representation>~, or
~@@<DBL,numeric representation>~) when it sees one of the following character
sequences:

.begin indent 4,8 tabs 9
a)\Any decimal digit which is not part of an identifier.
This will be the first digit of an ~INT~, ~REAL~, or
~DBL~.

b)\A @@<period,introducing REAL or DBL> followed by a digit.  This indicates the beginning
of a ~REAL~ or ~DBL~.

c)\A @@<dollar sign,introducing octal number> ($) followed by a digit.  This indicates the
start of an !<octal> (base 8) @<number,octal>, which is
simply another lexical representation of an ~INT~.
There may be one to twelve octal digits (0 through 7)
following the '$'.  The digits 8 and 9 are not allowed.

d)\A @@<percent sign,introducing relocatable line number> (%) followed by a digit.  This indicates the
.x relocatable line number
.x line number,relocatable
start of a relocatable integer, which has the property
of being changed whenever a line to which it refers
is renumbered.  There may be one to three decimal
digits after the percent sign.
.end

The arithmetic characteristics of numbers in
PPL are as follows:

An ~@@<INT,magnitude and precision>~ in @@<PPL-10,magnitude and precision in number> is capable of representing any
.xx number,magnitude,of
.x number,precision of
.xx PPL-10,precision of number,in
.xx PPL-11,precision of number,in
integer number from -34359738368 to 34359738367.
In @@<PPL-11,magnitude and precision in number>, the limits are -2147483648 to 2147483647.

A ~@@<REAL,magnitude and precision>~ in PPL-10 can represent, to approximately eight significant
digits' precision, a real number whose magnitude
is either zero or between approximately 1.4695E-39 and 1.7014E+38.
In PPL-11, the precision is only seven significant digits.

A ~@@<DBL,magnitude and precision>~ can represent, to approximately
sixteen digits of precision, any real number
within the limits given for ~REAL~s.

When @/<number,automatic printout/of>s are printed out by PPL,
either by the 'implied print' feature (simply
typing an expression on a line for evaluation)
or by the ~PRINT~ system function,
certain conventions are followed.
They are as follows:

An ~INT~, being inherently precise, is
printed to its full precision (up to eleven digits)
with leading zeroes suppressed.  No decimal
point is printed.

A ~REAL~ or ~DBL~ suffers from the problems
of conversion to and from the computer's internal
floating-point binary notation;
thus, few decimal numbers can be represented
'exactly'.  Though a ~REAL~ has
nearly seven or eight digits of precision, and a ~DBL~ nearly sixteen,
the last digit in either case is not particularly
reliable.

By convention, PPL rounds a ~REAL~ to seven
.x rounding of REAL and DBL
significant digits before printing, and a ~DBL~
to fifteen.  It then suppresses leading and
trailing zeroes.  A decimal point is always
printed.  Scientific notation is used if
.x scientific notation
the magnitude of the number is outside
the range 10{super(-3)} to 10{super(6)}.

A built-in function, called ~<<FORMAT>~,
.xx numeric output,alignment,of
.see number,formatting,FORMAT
is provided to allow user control over
numeric output formatting.  This is necessary,
for example, when attempting to format output
into columns.  ~FORMAT~ takes any number of arguments,
which it processes from left to right.

If an argument is of type ~@@<STRING,as format specification>~,
it is decoded and used as a !<format specification>
for future output by ~FORMAT~.  This specification
is composed of the following elements in the order given:

.begin indent 4,16 tabs 17
~E~ or ~D~\print in exponential format (with ~E~ or ~D~
and a two-digit exponent).  If this part of the
specification is omitted, standard (non-exponential)
decimal format is assumed.

!<n>Z\where !<n> is an integer less than 128, indicating
the number of <<zero-suppress>ed digit positions
to be allowed to the left of the decimal point.
If this specification is omitted, zero is assumed.

!<n>D\the number of non-zero-suppressed digit
positions to the left of the decimal point.

. (period)\indicates a decimal point is
to be printed (otherwise it is omitted, and
the next two specifications may not
be included).

!<n>D\the number of non-zero-suppressed digit
positions to the right of the decimal point.

!<n>Z\the number of zero-suppressed digit positions
to the right of the decimal point.
.end

If the format specification is ~"FF"~ or ~"FF."~,
it specifies printing in free format (including a period
in the specification causes a decimal point always to be printed).
Free format printing is the same as PPL's conventional
printing format except that rounding is done to one greater
digit of precision, i.e. 8 digits for a ~REAL~ and 16 for a ~DBL~.

If the argument is of type ~INT~, ~REAL~, or ~DBL~,
that number
is printed according to the most recent
format specification.  Blanks are substituted
for leading and trailing zeroes if they are in
zero-suppressed positions;  otherwise, the zeroes
are printed out.  If the number is negative,
the minus sign is printed in the last leading
zero-suppressed position (if there is one).
If the ~E~ or ~D~ specification has been
included, the number is adjusted by powers of ten
so as to exactly fill the leading
non-zero-suppressed places.

If the magnitude of a number is
too large to fit in all the leading positions,
an execution error occurs, with the
message "Number will not fit into current format".

The following examples illustrate some
uses of ~FORMAT~.
Note that like ~PRINT~, ~FORMAT~ does not output
a carriage return after printing a number;
this must be done explicitly by the user.

.examp
\FORMAT("3Z.4D", 7.41, 0.34168); ""
  7.4100   .3417
\FORMAT("3D.4Z", 7.41, 0.34168); ""
007.41  000.3417
\FORMAT("E1Z2D.4D", 7.41, 0.34168); ""
 74.1000E-01 34.1680E-02
.end

We can now use ~FORMAT~ to pretty up the
printout of the multiplication table of
{"Section!" forforms}:

.examp
\FORMAT("3Z1D")
\FOR I_1:8 DO (FOR J_1:8 DO FORMAT(I*J)); ""
   1   2   3   4   5   6   7   8
   2   4   6   8  10  12  14  16
   3   6   9  12  15  18  21  24
   4   8  12  16  20  24  28  32
   5  10  15  20  25  30  35  40
   6  12  18  24  30  36  42  48
   7  14  21  28  35  42  49  56
   8  16  24  32  40  48  56  64
.end
The PDP-11 version of PPL also includes a function ~<<CURRENT.FORMAT>~
which takes no arguments and returns the current ~FORMAT~ string.

.sec(Conversion Functions,conversion)
.x function,conversion

PPL contains built-in functions for
converting atomic data from one type to
another.  These are as follows:

.begin indent 0,8 tabs 9
.xx INT,conversion function
{fn(INT,a)}\The argument !<a> is converted and
returned as an ~INT~, where !<a> may be any
atomic value (~INT~, ~REAL~, ~DBL~, ~CHAR~, or ~BOOL~).
If !<a> is a ~REAL~ or ~DBL~, the fractional
part is truncated (removed).  If !<a> is a ~CHAR~,
it is converted to its equivalent 7<<ASCII>*
%<character/code>, which is a number in the range
0 to 127 (see {"Appendix!" appascii}).  If !<a> is a ~BOOL~,
the result is 1 if !<a> is ~TRUE~ and 0 if ~FALSE~.

.xx REAL,conversion function
{fn(REAL,a)}\The argument !<a> is converted
to a ~REAL~ and returned.  Conventions
for converting arguments of type ~BOOL~
and ~CHAR~ are the same as for {fn(INT,a)}.

.xx DBL,conversion function
{fn(DBL,a)}\Same as {fn(REAL,a)} except the
result is a ~DBL~.

.xx BOOL,conversion function
{fn(BOOL,a)}\Returns a ~BOOL~ean value
as follows:  an ~INT~, ~REAL~, or ~DBL~ is
converted to ~TRUE~ if nonzero and ~FALSE~
if zero.  A ~CHAR~ is converted to ~TRUE~
if and only if it is the character ~'T~
(upper or lower case).

.xx CHAR,conversion function
{fn(CHAR,a)}\The argument !<a> is converted to
a ~CHAR~acter as follows:  if the argument is
of type ~INT~, ~REAL~, or ~DBL~, the value
is used as a character code according to the
table in {"Appendix!" appascii} (this value is reduced
modulo 128 if it is outside the range zero through 127).
If !<a> is a ~BOOL~, the character
~'T~ is returned for ~TRUE~ and ~'F~ for ~FALSE~.
.end

The following are a few examples of the use of conversion functions:

.examp
\INT(137.45)
137
\REAL(-99)
-99.
\FOR I_65:90 DO PRINT(CHAR(I))
ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ
.end

Additionally, there is a function {fn(IDIV,a,b)} which is the same as
.see truncation,|IDIV, INT (function)|
{fn(DIV,a,b)} (the function invoked by the built-in '/' operator)
except that if both arguments are integers, the result is an
integer as well (i.e. with the remainder from the division
thrown away).  This makes {fn(IDIV,a,b)} approximately equivalent
to 3INT(DIV(!<a>,!<b>))1 when !<a> and !<b> are both ~INT~s, but without the
%<roundoff/error>s that might arise for large values of !<a> and !<b>.

It is often convenient to be able to convert values of any type
to the ~STRING~ which represents them, just as if the object were
to be printed out.
This provides the user with a powerful mechanism for writing his
own formatting routines or for processing non-~STRING~ values in
a character-oriented manner.
The two PPL versions provide somewhat different mechanisms for
this sort of operation.
On the PDP-10, the functions ~<<PRINTSTR>~ and ~<<FORMATSTR>~ are
defined, which operate in the same manner as ~PRINT~ and ~FORMAT~,
except that the resulting ~STRING~ value is returned as the value of
the function rather than being printed out.
In PPL-11, a more restricted facility is provided by the function
{fn(MSTRING,v)} which returns the ~STRING~ corresponding to the
argument !<v>, which may be any numerical value (~INT~, ~REAL~ or ~DBL~).

.sec(Mathematical Functions,mathfns)

PPL contains a small set of useful %<mathematical/function>s.  All take numeric arguments
(i.e. ~INT~, ~REAL~, or ~DBL~) and return
results of type ~REAL~ or ~DBL~.  (In @@<PPL-10,INT and DBL argument to mathematical function>, an argument of type ~INT~ or ~DBL~
is converted internally to a ~REAL~ during calculation;
thus the extra precision of an ~INT~ or a ~DBL~ is not utilized).

The %<trigonometric/function>s ~SIN~, ~COS~, and ~ATAN~
deal with angles expressed in <<radian>s.  To convert radians
to <<degree>s, multiply by 180/{pi}; to convert degrees
to radians, multiply by {pi}/180 (the value of {pi}, to
sixteen significant digits, is 3.141592653589793).

.begin indent 0,8 tabs 9
{fn(SIN,a)}\Sine of !<a>, where !<a> is an angle expressed
in radians.  The result is in the range -1.0 to 1.0.

.see cosine,COS
{fn(COS,a)}\Cosine of !<a>, where !<a> is an angle expressed
in radians.  The result is also in the range -1.0 to 1.0.

.see arctangent,ATAN
{fn(ATAN,a)}\Arctangent of !<a>, where !<a> is any ~REAL~ number.
The result is the principal value of the arctangent expressed
in radians, and is in the range -{pi}/2 to {pi}/2
(approximately -1.570796 to 1.570796).
.end

Most other trigonometric functions may be defined
in terms of the ones presented above; for example,
we might define the cotangent function as follows:

.examp
\$<<COT>(X)
   [1]\COT_COS(X)/SIN(X)
   [2]\$

\PI_3.141592653589793
\COT(PI/4)
1.
.end

The following are some other of PPL's built-in
mathematical functions.  These will give execution
errors if their arguments lie outside of certain
specified ranges.

.begin indent 0,8 tabs 9
.see square root,SQRT
{fn(SQRT,a)}\Square root of !<a>, which must be
greater than or equal to zero.  The result is
always greater than or equal
to zero.

.see logarithm,|LN, LOG|
{fn(LN,a)}\Natural (base !<e>) logarithm of !<a>,
which must be greater than zero.
The value of !<e> is 2.71828182845.
To get common (base 10) logarithms, multiply by
~1/LN(10)~, which is approximately .4342944819.

{fn(EXP,a)}\Exponential of !<a> (or !<e> to the !<a> power).
!<a> must be between about -88 and 88; the result is
always positive.  {fn(EXP,a)} is the inverse of {fn(LN,a)}.
.end

The following additional functions are included only in PPL-11.
(In PPL-10, these may easily be defined as user functions
in terms of existing built-in functions.)

.begin indent 0,8 tabs 9
.x PPL-11,ABS function
{fn(ABS,a)}\The absolute value of !<a>.

.x PPL-11,TAN function
{fn(TAN,a)}\Tangent of !<a> (radians).

.x PPL-11,LOG function
{fn(LOG,a)}\Common (base 10) logarithm of !<a>.
.end

The last built-in function to be discussed here,
called ~<<RANDOM>~, is used to generate !<pseudo-random>
.see pseudo-random,RANDOM
.see number,random,RANDOM
numbers.  By pseudo-random, we mean that, although the
numbers are generated by a deterministic, well-defined
process in the computer, there is no way for the normal user
or program to predict the next number in sequence;  further,
these pseudo-random numbers have certain statistical
properties with respect to uniform distribution and variance.
This function operates as follows:

.begin indent 0,12 tabs 13
{fn(RANDOM,a)}\For any value of !<a>, returns a pseudo-random
~REAL~ between zero and one (not inclusive).
The argument !<a>, which must be of type ~INT~, ~REAL~, or ~DBL~,
determines what (if any) initialization of the random number
generator is to take place.
.indent 12,12
If !<a>=0, the next random number in the present
sequence is generated; no initialization is performed.

If !<a><0, the random number generator is initialized
to an arbitrary quantity (actually a function of the
time of day), and the first random number in that sequence
is returned.

If !<a>>0, the random number generator is initialized to the
value !<a>, and the first random number in that sequence
is returned.  Repeatable random number sequences may thus be generated
by always initializing ~RANDOM~ to the same positive number.
This is sometimes useful when
controlled experiments are desired.
.end

When PPL is started up, an implicit call of 3RANDOM(-1)1
is made to ensure a different starting value for each session.
